public abstract class DataBuilder<T extends Bean,B extends DataBuilder<T,B>> extends Object implements ValueGenerator<T>, DelegateDataBuilder<T>
Base data "builder" class. Provides a facility for setting up property values and creating beans with those values.

When create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle), create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle), or create() execute, properties and populators are set and executed in ascending order according to their "order" values. Those with the same order value are executed according to the order in which they were set or added.

    • share

      public ValueGenerator<T> share()
      Returns a wrapper around this builder which can be handed to any method expecting a ValueGenerator<T>. The effect of this wrapper is to make sure that the builder is only called once as part of any create call. For example given: 
         MainBuilder mainBuilder = new MainBuilder();
   SubBuilder subBuilder = new SubBuilder();
   Main main = mainBuilder.withSubField1(subBuilder).withSubField2(subBuilder).create();
      You would normally get two entirely different Sub objects created; the SubBuilder would be called twice and the Main object would end up with field1 and field2 referencing two different objects. But if you did this: 
         MainBuilder mainBuilder = new MainBuilder();
   ValueGenerator<Sub> subBuilder = new SubBuilder().share();
   Main main = mainBuilder.withSubField1(subBuilder).withSubField2(subBuilder).create();
      The SubBuilder would only be called once and you'd have a single Main object whose field1 and field2 both reference a single Sub object.

      Note that the sharing only happens for a particular create call. A create call to create a graph of beans will only call the shared builder once. But an entirely separate create call will call it again e.g: 

         MainBuilder mainBuilder = new MainBuilder();
   ValueGenerator<Sub> subBuilder = new SubBuilder().share();
   Main main1 = mainBuilder.withSubField1(subBuilder).withSubField2(subBuilder).create();
   Main main2 = mainBuilder.withSubField1(subBuilder).withSubField2(subBuilder).create();
      Will create two Main objects, each of them pointing to a single Sub object. But the Sub object for main1 will be different from the one for main2
      Returns:
      a new value generator that will call the wrapped builder only once per create call

    • addPopulator

      protected final void addPopulator(Object id, int order, BeanPopulator<? super T> populator)
      Adds a BeanPopulator to the builder with the given id and order. If a prior BeanPopulator was already added with the same ID, then it is replaced with the given populator. A populator replacing an existing populator inherits the existing populator's place in the secondary ordering; i.e. populators are sorted first by their order field and second by the placement order - the order in which they were added. If populator B replaces populator A then it will have its own order field but it will inherit A's placement order
      Parameters:
      id - the object with which to refer to the populator, in future calls to getPopulator(Object) or removePopulator(Object)
      order - used to select when this populator gets executed during create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle)
      populator - the populator to execute during create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle)

    • set

      protected final void set(IPropertyInfo property, Object value)
      Sets the value to assign to a property when a new bean is create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle)d. The property is set with an order value of DEFAULT_ORDER. The behavior of this method depends on the property. There are three general classes of property: link, array, and scalar.

      If the property is a link (aka "foreign key") property, then the value may either be a KeyableBean, a Key, a DataBuilder, or null.

      If the property is an array property, then the value may either be a Collection, an array, or null. If it is null, or an empty collection or array, then the array is cleared, i.e., all previously added elements are removed (and DEFAULT_ORDER is used as the order value for all further elements added for that property). Otherwise, the collection or array may contain any combination of non-null values allowed for link properties (KeyableBean, Key, or DataBuilder).

      If the property is a scalar property, then the value must either be an instance of the property type, a ValueGenerator for the property type, or null.

      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - under any of the following circumstances:
      • The property is not a datamodel property.
      • The property does not exist on this builder's entity type.
      • The value is not compatible with the property type. E.g., the value is a number, but the property is of type String.
      See Also:
      • create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle)

    • setLocalizedFieldFromDisplayKey

      protected final void setLocalizedFieldFromDisplayKey(IPropertyInfo propertyInfo, String displayKey)
      Sets the name of the displaykey to resolve when a new bean is create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle)d.

      The property to set is identified by a PropertyReference,which can be obtained with the Gosu syntax entityname#propertyname.

      The property is set with an order value of DEFAULT_ORDER. The behavior of this method is that for each LanguageType configured in the system the displaykey is resolved and that value is used to set the given property value the language.

      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - under any of the following circumstances:
      • The property is not a datamodel property.
      • The property does not exist on this builder's entity type.
      IllegalStateException - is the property is not localized
      See Also:
      • create(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle)

    • wrapBean

      public static <BT extends KeyableBean> ValueGenerator<BT> wrapBean(BT bean)
      Utility, takes any bean and wraps it in an ExistingBean object so it can be passed to any method that takes a ValueGenerator<T>. This is useful when creating withXXX methods that can take either a bean or a builder. First create a core method that takes a ValueGenerator<T>; all builders are value generators so this method will accept a builder. To provide an overloaded method that takes a bean, add a method whose body is withXXX(wrapBean(bean)).
      Parameters:
      bean - the bean to be wrapped
      Returns:
      a new value generator that will return the given bean when its create method is called

    • wrapValue

      public static <V> ValueGenerator<V> wrapValue(V value)
      Utility, takes any value and wraps it in a ValueGenerator<T>. This is useful when creating withXXX methods that can take either a raw value or a ValueGenerator. First create a core method that takes a ValueGenerator<T>. To provide an overloaded method that takes a raw value, add a method whose body is withXXX(wrapValue(T)).
      Parameters:
      value - the raw value to be wrapped
      Returns:
      a new value generator that will return the given value when its create method is called
